By Gao Honghao, Guan Yiwen and Yu Yangyang, CAIJING reporters

Editor | Song Wei

The new coronavirus (COVID-19) is invisible and scary, and it is highly infectious, has a long incubation period, and has a low mortality compared to SARS and Mers, which have previously attacked humans. It also does not discriminate on the basis of age, sex, race or nationality.

As long as there is a source of infection, cruise ships at sea are not immune. The 290-metre-long and 37.5-metre-wide diamond princess is the seventh-largest ship in the Princess Fleet and, although not the largest, is one of the world's best-equipped luxury liners. Its Hull is pure white, and its sky-blue bottom blends with the sea, giving it an elegant, serene look. It has 18 decks, and when night falls over a dark sea, the ship looks like a small, brightly lit city.

Now, the luxury liner has the highest number of confirmed cases of the new coronavirus in the world, except in China.

Since February 3,2020, the ship has docked at the port of Tahei in Yokohama, Japan. More than 2,000 passengers from more than 50 countries and regions have been quarantined, and they have been asked not to leave their 20-square-meter or so cabins, meals are delivered to the door by the crew in shifts, and their only free time of the day is to go on deck for an hour and breathe the fresh air outside the cabin in batches.

In addition to more than 2,000 passengers, there were more than 1,000 crew members on board. They work dozens of hours a day, busily disinfecting cruises and cooking for their passengers. The crew, who are at greater risk of contracting the virus, are arranged to eat simple meals together, live in cabins much smaller than the passenger rooms and share a bathroom for all four.

The original source of the infection was an 80-year-old passenger from Hong Kong, China, who disembarked in Hong Kong on January 25 and was confirmed to have contracted the new coronavirus on February 1. The 3,711-person luxury liner was ordered to be quarantined by the Japanese government on Feb. 3, two days after it returned to its home port in Yokohama a day earlier than planned.

Since the 19th, about 943 passengers have returned to land after 14 days in isolation. But instead of stopping the spread of the virus, the ship-wide quarantine accelerated its spread. The remaining 2,768 remained in quarantine, including the entire crew, meaning that 621 people may not be the ship's final confirmed number.

The cruise ship confirmed the number of dozens of people a day at a rate of increase, the highest number of new confirmed one-day 99 new infections. In two weeks, the total number of confirmed cases on board increased from 10 to 621, with two deaths. The medical community noted that the virus on the ship appeared to be particularly insidious, with 321 of the 621 confirmed cases of asymptomatic infection, accounting for more than 50 percent.

Kentaro Iwata, an infectious disease specialist at Kobe University Hospital in Japan, managed to board the ship with DMAT, an infectious disease specialist who had lived through SARS and Zaire ebolavirus, in a video posted to social media on the evening of February 18th, he told what he had seen on the ship:

"The diamond princess is a production machine for a new coronavirus. I was so shocked by what I saw on the boat that I nearly fainted. In more than 20 years of epidemic prevention work, I have never felt so much risk of infection. Even the Basic Green Zone (uninfected) and the red zone (possibly infected with a virus) are indistinguishable on a cruise ship. No one on board is a specialist in infection control, only the officials are doing the layman's work."

But the Ministry of Health, Labour and Welfare has released very limited information about the ship, which is being watched around the world. In addition to the number of confirmed cases, information about the nationality, age and gender of the infected people is sometimes mixed, there's even less information on the cruise ship.

Every day, government workers in Hazmat suits are seen picking up the latest confirmed cases of the disease, a white mystery bus with curtains drawn enters and exits the port, while those quarantined on the cruise ship can only watch from a distance. No one knows what really happened.

"What happened inside the ship in the last two weeks? Because the Japanese government has not provided any information about what happened inside the ship in the last two weeks, " Iwada asked in the video. Iwata's video has been deleted, and he declined to be interviewed by CAIJING.

The diamond princess is a unique and typically complex example of an infectious disease in the global new Crown Epidemic:

At the viral level, Professor Liu Liyuan of the Beijing Normal University sees the cruise ship as "a highly ideal residential building model for the Wuhan new coronavirus infection experiment" due to its special closed environment.

The ever-increasing number of confirmed cases testifies to the enormous limitations of isolation in such a well-equipped and modern space, and to the universal vulnerability of all human beings, as evidenced by the fact that all categories of people on board are infected; The fact that large-scale transmission still occurred despite the intervention of professionals shows that the virus can be transmitted in a variety of ways, including droplets, contact, Aerosol transmission and even faecal-oral transmission; and can be verified in cruise ships, is it possible for the virus to spread through air conditioning and ventilation systems, sewer systems. And among those diagnosed, the proportion of asymptomatic infections is rising, from 56% to 70% to 76% . Does this mean the virus is less virulent and more contagious?

At the cruise level, this is a ship docked in a Japanese port, registered in the UK, operating the main body of the United States, who should be responsible for? All along, the international cruise responsibility has always been a world-wide problem, authority and responsibility has led to delays in the prevention and control of the epidemic.

"This is the most complex crisis in the history of world cruise ships since the titanic incident in 1909, " Sun Siqi, a lecturer at the Law School of Shanghai Maritime University and author of "essentials of Cruise Tourism Law" , told CAIJING

At the national level, few people are aware of Japan's own situation: First, it is not an obligation Japan must fulfill; Second, japan needs to take into account the limited availability of medical supplies, the risk of widespread transmission in the country, the risk of impact on the national economy, and the consideration of each political party and politician for the fate of their own future. These complex and contradictory factors make the whole of Japan into a conflict, but also the diamond princess put the ship into danger.

In a way, the diamond princess reflects the frailty of human society, perhaps because of the insoluble question of whether to let a train hit a child playing on the track or send a busload of people into an abyss, one netizen commented.

Two weeks, from one to 621

##Two weeks, from one to 621

Through a long gangway covered with sky-blue tarps, the Diamond Princess's first group of about 500 passengers finally landed on February 19, "This is the last tunnel to greet the world, " sighs a Hong Kong passenger.

They had been isolated at sea for 14 days, and it was nice to be back on land. Even the morning's "yard time" on the deck became precious to the Hong Kong tourist. "This is the last deck moment before we leave, and it will be history, " she said.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
(Chinese Hong Kong Tourist Yardley's deck time Twitter@ Yardley  Wong, Feb. 19)

It will be a special and memorable experience for the 3,711 people on the diamond princess, but no one wants to go through it again.

On the afternoon of February 1st, the whistle of the cruise ship sounded on time, the happy passengers on Okinawa had returned to the ship, and the diamond princess was on her way to her final stop at Yokohama, they are about to conclude their 16-day voyage to Southeast Asia in early spring.

Amid the Hubbub, few noticed a news flash on public television: A former passenger on the diamond princess, visitors who disembarked in Hong Kong, China, on January 25th were diagnosed with new pneumonia -- a virulent virus that by then had forced the country to lock down cities, infecting 11,821 people and killing 259.

Soon, the news was drowned out. On the 11th day of the trip, the tourists aren't tired, so they grab their last moments on the cruise: Gamblers and the spectators at the wheel, swigging in the high end cafeteria, psychedelic steam rising from the SPA area to attract the ladies. After all, they paid from 250,000 yen (about 16,000 yuan) to 1,382,000 yen (about 89,000 yuan) .

CAIJING reporters learned that on that day, only the crew members were summoned for an emergency meeting, but the top performance is still calm. The meeting was played down, and the manager just said, don't panic, take precautions. It was a relief to the nervous crew.

"It was agreed that there was only one patient on board and he had already left the ship, so there was no need to be afraid, " Zhang Chi, a Chinese sailor, told Caijing. Only 22 of the ship's crew were from China, and half of its more than 1,000 crew were from the Philippines -- Florida -- and they were less nervous about the outbreak.

The crew then enjoyed a brief orgy. Although living conditions are not good, they know how to make the best of a bad situation, such as going to the gym together and starting a group meeting. The ship was bustling with people both inside and outside.

A tourist posted a video on social media of the cruise ship singing a Japanese folk song before it arrived in Yokohama. The oldest passenger was 91. The video shows people humming, nodding and shaking their bodies to the melody, with printed lyrics in their hands. The entire concert hall and the stairs were filled with passengers, all holding their breath for fear that a single noise would break the moment.

"It was supposed to be our last day on the ship, " the tourist wrote. "It was my first cruise and it was amazing how good it was. "

Few people realize that cruise ships are Sleeper Cell now.

In the eyes of epidemic prevention experts, there are too many ways for a cruise ship to transmit the virus, which exists in the air that tourists breathe every day, in frequent contact with gambling tables, dining tables, swimming pools, dance floors, Internet cafes and shops.

Another member of the crew of the diamond princess told Caijing that before each cruise, tourists would be gathered in a fixed group space on the ship to listen to safety broadcasts lasting from half an hour to an hour, this could be the perfect time for the virus to spread. One of the largest collective spaces is an 800 seat theatre.

"The diamond princess is obviously not aware of the risks, " a senior cruise operator told Caijing on January 15,2020, large luxury cruise ships of the same type as the diamond princess have repatriated all the Chinese crew members from their original service vessels with full pay, in an attempt to minimize the risks in every respect.

"The princess may have the most relaxed management on several luxury cruise ships, " the crew said.

He says employees here have a lot of freedoms they don't have on other cruises, such as not wearing a name tag in the staff area or wearing slippers in staff bars. On Royal Caribbean cruises, by contrast, it is against the rules for crew members to show their toes in the staff area, not to mention wearing slippers.

"On some princess ships, it may be because the hull is so old that even the monitoring system is not fully installed, " the crew member told reporters, meaning that in many cases the crew would have to be supervised entirely by manpower.

It was not until about 4 p.m. on 3 February that the captain of the ship made a public announcement to all passengers. That evening, the ship returned to its home port in Yokohama, Japan, a day earlier than planned, and the Ministry of Health, Labour and Welfare quarantine team immediately boarded the ship for an overnight inspection.

The first batch of test results were announced on the morning of February 5 through the captain's announcement, "10 people have been confirmed infected. " But until February 4, the day before the ship's quarantine, tourists still gathered in the dining hall to eat as usual, the crew continues to serve.

From 5 February, the ship was ordered by the Japanese government to quarantine the whole ship for 14 days. Three days later, the Cruise 208 personnel involved in the testing, has a cumulative number of confirmed 64 cases, the confirmed rate of nearly one-third.

By this time the unease and anxiety began to diffuse. One tourist said she took her temperature at least seven times in a few hours.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
(photo / afp / Getty Images) # The diamond princess cruises in Port of Yokohama, Japan, on February 10,2020

On 10 February and 12 February, 65 and 39 new cases were confirmed, respectively, especially on 12 February, when the media reported that an official involved in quarantine had been diagnosed, wearing gloves to wipe away sweat from the ship, and reapply the mask he had removed from his face. The news made passengers nervous, as they received little protection.

After seeing the news, the tourist, who had taken his temperature seven times in a few hours, began to feel as if his throat was getting itchy. He didn't know whether it was from allergies, or cold, or the dry air, or are you showing the first signs of the virus? He took his temperature at least five more times that day.

A total of 44 new cases were confirmed on 13 February, 67 on 15 February, 70 on 16 February, and a staggering 99 new cases were confirmed on 17 February until 19 February, when a total of 621 cases were confirmed in 3,011 individual tests, nearly one out of every three people tested on the cruise ship had a confirmed case.

The figures are alarming, and a hasty quarantine of the entire ship seems useless.

The news that the next five crew members had been diagnosed added to the unease. Dowle, 63, from Canada, suffers from asthma, he and his wife said in an interview with foreign media on the 13th, "Once the virus gets to the crew, there's a full outbreak. We're isolated, but we're eating their food. I feel like I'm sitting ducks here. "

On February 19th the Institute of Medical Science published its first full report on the diamond princess. According to the report, based on the number of confirmed cases before the date of onset, there is clear evidence of significant transmission of the new coronavirus on board the ship before quarantine was imposed on 5 February.

For everyone on board, the days of quarantine were a long wait, for the day the quarantine ended, or for the day they were notified of their diagnosis.

Chaotic system

##Chaotic system

In a panic, the ship's already relatively loose management system began to become disorderly, which in part accelerated the spread of the virus.

One incident occurred six days after the ship was quarantined. On the night of February 11, five crew members -- Room Service, restaurant staff and duty free store manager -- were confirmed on land. The crew was in a panic, and in their working group, the manager and staff quarreled.

Zhang Chi told Caijing that a dozen Japanese workers were constantly expressing concerns, demanding to stop working and get off the ship and go home. Plastic surgeons who were good at English were asked to temporarily take on the role of interpreter, but translators were required to keep in touch with guests and crew members, they think the job is too dangerous and refuse to accept it.

A variety of demands poured in, and the manager had no choice but to keep arguing that he was merely relaying orders from above. But that didn't stop employees from complaining, and soon the manager angrily backed out of the group.

The CAIJING reporter learned that the crew members of the diamond princess knock on the door every day to take the temperature of the tourists, but this is not a compulsory act. The crew members will seek the opinions of the tourists, and if the tourists refuse, the crew members can not force it.

The quarantine on the diamond princess was no different from the ship's traditional standard of isolation: only those with fever were sent to a sterile, empty room for isolation. People who have been in close contact with someone with a fever are not isolated.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
CAIJING reporter learned that on the evening of the 19th, a Chinese sailor working in a cruise SPA center developed fever, cough and other symptoms. She then went to her doctor's room alone with a mask. After the doctor gave her medicine, she went to the isolation room on her own.

The isolation measures on the ship are not standard. The guest rooms of the passengers who have disembarked are transformed into fever isolation places after disinfecting. The crew has been tested, but because the test results have not come out, as of the "Caijing" reporter, the crew has not been off the ship.

According to "CAIJING" reporter statistics, the diamond princess, the proportion of asymptomatic infection is quite high, 1 in 2 people for asymptomatic infection, the proportion of 51.7% . This means that a large number of asymptomatic infected people are becoming carriers of the virus because they have not been detected in time and have not been isolated.

A crew member told reporters that from beginning to end, the ship's protective materials only masks, has not been equipped with more professional virus infection medical staff, some crew until February 19 was still working.

"when the ship is in a state of emergency, the crew will have to clean the whole ship every half an hour, and the Princess's disinfectant needs to be replenished by the crew in a fixed place, and there will be frequent contact between the crew, " a crew member told Caijing.

Zhang Chi said he was most worried about air conditioning, but he was still beating a drum when the ship brought in experts from the United States and Japan, all saying that the air conditioning was clean, not contagious, and that he was already using as much fresh air as possible, it feels like the virus is everywhere.

A Japanese infectious disease control expert, who asked not to be named, told Caijing that the isolation of the entire ship was the easiest thing to do, but it was only the first step, and further internal intervention was needed, such as setting up three zones on the ship, this includes clean areas, mixing areas and contaminated areas. In clean areas where there is no obvious history of contact with a confirmed patient, management must be maintained and more disinfection must be done to reduce human activity in the area.

But on the diamond princess, after the ship was quarantined, follow-up containment was chaotic.

Ministry of Health, Labour and Welfare, a deputy minister, posted a picture on twitter showing the diamond Princess's isolation measures on two adjacent gates leading to the same indoor space, the Japanese words "clean road" and "unclean road" are pasted on them. The tweet was later deleted.

"The tweet was deleted, but I'm glad he knows what the problem is -- Harvard is as clean as it gets, " Iwada said

At one point, Iwada, who lived through SARS and Ebola, managed to get on a cruise ship, but was shocked by what he saw there. "For more than 20 years, I never worried about getting infected because I knew how to protect myself and others and how to control the infection. But inside the ship, I was terrified of being infected with the new coronavirus, because I had no way of knowing where it was. There's no Green Zone, there's no red zone, there's a virus everywhere, and everyone can get infected by it."

Zhang Chi, the Chinese crew member of the Diamond Princess, confirmed Iwada's claim to Caijing.

"It could be random human contact, pollution in the air, food pollution, even feces. Now cruise ships need to figure out what is infecting the virus, or it's very dangerous to blind yourself,"Jin Dongyan, a virologist and professor of biochemistry at the University of Hong Kong's School of Medicine, told Caijing.

Yang Gonghuan, former deputy director of the Chinese Center for Disease Control and Prevention, told the CAIJING reporter that, "With so many people gathered in such a small environment, there was no way to ventilate the cabin, and if you had to ventilate the deck regularly, there was actually a high risk of cross-contamination. For cruise ships, the best thing to do is to remove these people from the ship and move them to a more dispersed area."

Yang Gonghuan pointed out to the "CAIJING" reporter that the same truth contrast to the domestic, in Wuhan, experts gradually realized that home isolation effect is not so good, so now adjust measures, confirmed infection to a shelter hospital.

In its 19 February report, "ON-SITE BRIEFING: the case of the diamond princess new coronaviruses, " Niid noted that, given the nature of the cruise ship, it was not possible to isolate everyone individually, and that sharing the cabin was necessary in such cases, and some crew members must continue to perform their duties to keep the ship running, so many are still working, which makes the isolation incomplete.

The crew said the ship was supposed to be the safest because most of the passengers on the diamond princess were Japanese and were hygienic and protective. So he was just a Watch the fires burning across the river when the country was suffering from pneumonia, but now he realized it was "fire at the city gate and fish in the pond" .

Hard way off the boat

##Hard way off the boat

The diamond princess is a good example of an infectious agent that proves the limits of physical isolation in the face of new coronaviruses, and the current quarantine protocol on cruise ships has been met with skepticism from both Chinese and foreign experts. Why, then, does the Japanese government insist on keeping tourists and sailors off the ship?

A number of Japanese experts interviewed by Caijing gave a more consistent answer: First, Japan's medical conditions do not allow large-scale passengers to large-scale disembarkation; The other is that the current Anbe administration is driven by political and economic considerations.

'The first principle of finding an infected person in a space must be to isolate the infected person, the suspected infected person, from other people, ' Hayang Shikasaka, president of the Asian Society for Cell Therapy, which supports the Japanese government's approach, told Caijing. Mass migration of more than 3,000 people is not the best approach at this point, especially as Japan's public health resources are not adequately prepared.

A person from the Japanese medical system told the reporter that at present there are about 160,000 hospital beds including clinics in Japan, but there are less than 1,900 hospital beds specially equipped for treating infectious diseases, accounting for only 0.1% of the total, and it's spread all over the country, so it can't be called immediately.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Even with all the beds, the cost of isolating, caring for, boarding and quarantining 3,000 people would be a huge expense.

"It's not just beds, but there is a general shortage of everything Japanese hospitals need to deal with the new coronavirus, " a person close to Japan's health care system told CAIJING. In the case of face masks, it's not just people who can't buy them, even many of Japan's biggest hospitals have only a few thousand in stock.

Apart from hospitals, Japanese authorities have struggled to find isolated hotels that can accommodate more than 3,000 visitors. "hotels in Japan are almost all privately owned and the government has no power to expropriate them. "

When the Japanese evacuated their overseas Chinese from Wuhan in February and sought quarantine facilities for the returned Japanese citizens, only one hotel in Chiba Prefecture agreed to accept more than 100 people, and the rest could only be quarantined at home, depending on the severity of the situation, the source told CAIJING, or stay in government facilities with limited beds, such as tax universities and research institutes.

Nor, he says, Can Japan follow China's lead in putting cruise passengers in stadiums or makeshift hospitals.

An expert in the field of cruise ships, Dr. Chen Haibo of the School of law of Ningbo University, analyzed to the reporter from Caijing, "The easiest way to apply the existing legislation is for the Japanese government to prevent all travellers from being isolated on land initially. Based on the transmission characteristics of the new coronavirus, the whole ship isolation can physically isolate the ship and the people on board from the people on shore, in order to protect the people on shore from the virus."

Some analysts questioned why the Japanese government did not quickly test all tourists, so that they can quickly uninfected tourists off the ship. But according to the reporter understanding, with Japan's current detection mode, want to achieve rapid detection is not realistic.

Under the ban Haoyang told reporters that Japan currently uses the PCR detection method, a batch of detection time is about 5-6 hours, only 80 local institutions in the country are able to carry out such detection, that means it will take at least two weeks for all to be tested.

However, a person close to the Institute of Medical Science told Caijing that the institute, Joint-stock Company and others have now developed a simple kit, the new reagent will give results in 15 minutes.

"The joint-stock Company plant in Dalian, China, has produced 250,000 kits, but when and how much depends on how seriously the Japanese government takes them, " the people said. At present, the testing reagent caught up with the cruise ship quarantine period of the end of the remaining passengers have completed all the testing.

Indeed, there is a deeper reason for the farcical isolation: The Japanese government does not want to be "targeted" by the WHO.

According to the World Health Organization's current regulations, infected tourists on board ships are not counted in Japan's own data. But once confirmed patients are picked up from the ship and treated in Japanese hospitals, they are counted in the Japanese case count.

As of 21:00 GMT, 19 February, the total number of confirmed cases of COVID-19 infection in Japan has exceeded 700, reaching 704. But of those, 621 were from the Diamond Princess, compared with 83 in Japan.

If the number of cases in Japan continues to rise, World Health Organization will have to re evaluate the security environment in Japan, which will have a significant impact on the Japanese economy.

"because of China's epidemic, many Japanese companies that set up factories in China have been hit hard, " a longtime industry observer told reporters. Many parts and components from Toyota, Nissan and Honda are made in China, honda's four plants, for example, are all in Wuhan because of the outbreak. Once Japan itself became a serious epidemic, the blow to the economy was self-evident.

While the United States has closed almost all U.S. and Chinese airlines, Singapore and Australia have barred travelers from China for the past 14 days, Japan has imposed fairly mild restrictions, barring only the Hubei and Zhejiang regions, the people said, this shows that the Japanese government is very serious about the economy, and therefore will try to prevent the diamond princess may bring all the negative impact on the Japanese economy.

Once targeted by World Health Organization, the bigger impact will be on Tokyo, Japan, which will host the Olympics this summer.

"The Olympics are very important to Japan, " Xu Jingbo, a Waseda University special lecturer who has long studied Japanese political culture, told CAIJING.

In 1964, Japan hosted the first Olympic Games. Since then, the whole country has undergone tremendous changes. Shinkansen, TV sets and automobiles have appeared one after another, japan has entered a golden age of rapid modernization.

ANBE's party, he said, would not allow the games to go awry in a country that has hosted the Olympics again half a century after they were supposed to do so, as a sign that Japan's strength was still there.

Japan is expected to spend more than $25 billion to prepare for the Tokyo Olympics.

At a news conference on Feb. 14 between the International Olympic Committee and the Work Coordination Committee of the Tokyo Organizing Committee, IOC President Cotts said, based on advice provided by WHO, the 2020 Tokyo Olympics will begin on time. But then, on the 15th, the WHO rejected the International Olympic Committee's suggestion that the Tokyo Games need not be postponed.

"It shows that the WHO still has reservations about the development of the epidemic in Japan, and if the number of confirmed cases continues to grow, World Health Organization warns that the Tokyo Olympics will not go smoothly, which is a huge blow to the Anbe administration. "

Against the backdrop of Japan's health care shortage, 3,711 tourists and crew were forced to spend two weeks on a cruise ship in a concentrated isolation as the government weighed economic and political prudence.

On Feb. 19, the first 500 passengers began disembarking from the cruise ship. All of them tested negative for the new coronavirus, and some of the passengers took public transportation home. Passengers are scheduled to disembark within three days from the 19th to the 21st, while crew members remain in quarantine.

At the same time, Alice, a Canadian passenger, looked out of her window and saw that the infected passenger was no longer in an ambulance alone, but had been "upgraded" to a white bus with multiple confirmed passengers. "This is the result of the continued spread of the virus and the overwhelming burden on the Japanese health system, " she said.

Who is responsible for the cruise ship?

##Who is responsible for the cruise ship?

Passengers were not allowed to disembark, all were placed in isolation in their cabins, and the entire crew was unable to be tested for reagents. In the past two weeks, a series of "perverse" rescues has turned the world's attention to Japan's nebulous government.

"people walk around in Ppe [ personal protective equipment ] , eat in the same place and even wear protective gloves when they eat. There was total chaos, there was no professional infection control staff on board, there was no professional staff to prevent infection, and laymen were in charge of everything,"Iwada said in the video, describing the rescue scene he saw after he boarded the ship.

According to Iwada, the Japanese sent no infectious disease experts, only medical teams and officials from the Ministry of Health, Labour and Welfare, in Darmat.

"It is clear that the Japanese authorities did not make an adequate assessment of the situation inside the ship, or whether they felt it necessary to pour too much resources into it, " a person close to Japan's health care system told CAIJING.

The blame has been placed on the Japanese government for its negligence, which led to the current disaster.

Sun Siqi, a lecturer at the School of Law of Shanghai Maritime University and author of the Law on cruise tourism, told Caijing that although Japan does not have sufficient estimates of the development of the situation, it also has a certain negative attitude towards the rescue, but that does not make the Japanese government solely responsible for the accident.

"This is the most complex crisis in the history of the world's cruise industry since the titanic in 1909, " he said, adding that in many ways there was no precedent for current laws, responsibilities or rescue methods.

The primary complexity lies in the subject of responsibility. Whether Japan has the responsibility and obligation to regulate the cruise directly determines whether the Japanese authorities treat the cruise ship lightly or tightly.

According to public records, the Diamond Princess's parent company, the Miami based Carnival Cruise Lines, is the main operator; the ship is London based and its flag state is the UK; and it is now based in Port of Yokohama, Japan.

In the United Nations Convention on the Law of the Sea, the flag state shall effectively exercise jurisdiction and control over administrative, technical and social matters relating to ships flying its flag. According to the United Nations Convention on the Law of the Sea and many IMO maritime conventions, the Flag State exists throughout the operation of a ship.

However, in this cruise epidemic, the outside world did not see the flag of the United Kingdom.

Chen Haibo to "CAIJING" reporter analysis, "there is no pressure or incentive for flag states to 'step up' without having to take on commercial risks and responsibilities in place of shipping companies. The industry is also examining whether flag states should be held accountable, particularly for the serious loss of life and pollution of the marine environment, and how to avoid negative treatment by flag states."

Previously, Japanese officials had argued that the space above the ship was not Japanese territory by law, and that it would be difficult to carry out medical treatment.

Hiro Uchihiro, Director of the nonprofit organization, told Caijing that Japan still follows a set of port quarantine laws that have been in place since the Meiji era in 1899, that is, when a disease is found on a foreign ship, Japan has the right to prohibit the members of the ship from entering the country.

However, the flag state's jurisdiction over the ship is limited to the high seas. Once a ship enters a state's port, the state has jurisdiction under the Convention on the international regime of seaports over foreign ships located in its port. That is, in practice, although states generally do not intervene in internal events, ships will still take the coastal state and flag state jurisdiction combined approach.

Sun said that both Japan's claim that "cruise ships are not Japanese territory" and the outside world's criticism of Japan have some truth. But since no similar case has ever been made in international cruise history, it is not yet possible to determine which is most responsible, Japan or Britain.

But what is clear is that Japan had the right to deny cruise ships access to port in the first place. Just as at the time of the incident, another cruise ship sailing on the sea, the ship has been refused entry to Taiwan, Japan, the Philippines, Thailand, Guam (United States territorial acquisitions) and other ports.

The diamond princess is so special that Japan has to take on a hot potato again.

Xu Jingbo, president of the Asia News Agency and a special lecturer at the Waseda University, told Caijing that the diamond princess was carrying 1,285 Japanese tourists, more than 35 percent of whom are Japanese citizens, and the Japanese government can not abandon them

Second, the Diamond Princess, which was launched in 2004 by Mitsubishi Heavy Industries'Nagasaki Shipyard, was the first luxury cruise ship to have its home port in Japan, making a significant contribution to the country's cruise and tourism industries.

"The so-called 'don't abandon your people at sea, don't be ungrateful' is something the Japanese insist on, " Xu said. But psychologically, the Japanese government was certainly reluctant to take over, so it ultimately opted for a more moderate approach.

The princess does not call at Port, but stays at sea in the port area, close to land only when it needs to be resupplied and evacuated. According to the international law, the maritime domain is called "Florida -- the Exclusive Economic Zone Sea area" .

"The closer the land, the greater the interference and psychological acceptance of the coastal state. Although the diamond princess has entered the port area, it is still anchored some distance from the land, which has partly contributed to the ambiguous attitude of the Japanese authorities, " Yu Yaodong, an associate professor at the Shanghai Maritime University, told Caijing.

"This is not a legal and medical crisis in Japan, but a humanitarian crisis, " he added.

The difference of speech and action between different dialects

##The difference of speech and action between different dialects

As the world becomes increasingly aware of the diamond princess outbreak, passengers have begun to hand in joint letters to their countries in the hope that countries and regions will send charter flights to take them home as soon as possible.

According to incomplete statistics from Japan's Health, Labor and Welfare Bureau, official and Public Accounts of Princess cruises, about one-third of the Japanese people on the Diamond Princess Cruise, more than 1,000, and about 428 Americans, there are about 352 people in Hong Kong, 255 in Canada, 200 in Australia, 40 in Britain, 35 in Italy, 24 in Russia, 24 in Taiwan, 15 in Israel and 14 in South Korea, new Zealanders, about 13 people.

The United States was the first to decide on a charter flight. The two American planes arrived in Japan on February 16. They departed from Tokyo International Airport in the morning and afternoon of February 17. After arriving at Air Force bases in California and Texas, all passengers were separated for another 14 days.

An American couple filmed themselves disembarking on the night of February 16, a man in a protective suit guides them through the process of getting off the ship "walk on, show your passport to the man in the yellow suit, hand it over to the Defense Department on the other side, hold your passports, put you in a car, take you to the airport, fly you back to the United States. "

"when the time comes, I will step into the vast world! " The American couple can not contain their joy.

Matthew wasn't on the charter flight with the rest of the team. Of the 428 Americans aboard the ship, 338 were aboard the two charter flights, with 44 confirmed infected Americans remaining in Japan for treatment, meaning that about 40 Americans, both crew and passengers, were on board, matthew was one of them.

The United States government has ruled that no one who was able to board the two charter flights can enter the United States until March 4, two weeks after they were allowed off the ship on Feb. 19, when the Japanese government ended its quarantine.

On Social Media, Matthew expressed his choice to stay in Florida because he did not want to be quarantined for another 14 days and, more importantly, because he was worried about being in close quarters with more than 300 people who did not get the test results.

As it turned out, Matthew's concerns were not overblown. On the evening of the two chartered flights returning from Japan, the United States said that 14 of the passengers who had previously returned to the United States by charter from Japan had been diagnosed with the infection and were immediately quarantined on board, four of them have been transferred to a California facility, and 10 have been transferred to the University of Nebraska Medical Center for treatment.

With the US sending a chartered plane, Australia also sent a chartered plane to bring its nationals back on February 19 and New Zealanders can also take it. Canada, Italy, South Korea, Hong Kong, Taiwan have also sent or plan to send charter flights, South Korea even sent the presidential plane "Air Force 3" to transfer four South Koreans and a Japanese spouse who want to return home; The Israeli government said all three of its passengers on board had been infected, the first confirmed cases in Israel.

Japan, struggling to cope with the diamond princess, has had to turn down another ship, the Amsterdam, which is trying to dock in Japan. The cruise ship, carrying more than 2,000 people, has been shut out of ports in at least five countries or regions and has been "wandering" at sea for two weeks, on February 12, the ship was finally accepted by Cambodia to dock and arrived in Cambodia on the morning of the 13th.

In stark contrast to the diamond princess, the passengers of the ship were greeted warmly by Cambodia immediately after it was confirmed that the test results of more than 20 fever patients on board the ship were negative, the Prime Minister, Hun Sen, also visited Sihanoukville, where he welcomed the first passengers without a mask, shaking hands, hugging and laying flowers.

However, the new coronavirus did not spare the people of the ship, the first batch of passengers ashore, an 83-year-old American female passenger left Cambodia, two days later in Malaysia was diagnosed with the new coronavirus.

On February 19, the Cambodian Ministry of Health announced that none of the passengers and crew still in Cambodia had been tested for the new coronavirus, it also stressed that the ship should not be compared to the diamond princess, which has detected a large number of confirmed cases.

The Cambodian Prime Minister, Hun Sen, has also raised the prospect of hosting a large welcome banquet for cruise passengers still in Cambodia and a tour of the capital. Hun Sen said in a video released on Feb. 18 that he made the decision to "welcome" the cruise ship after the U.S. Embassy in Cambodia told the Cambodian government that it had been refused permission to dock by several countries.

In Cambodia, this was no longer a public health event, and the new coronavirus gave Hun Sen an unprecedented opportunity to assume the mantle of a passionate and humanitarian nation.

But for the people of the Diamond Princess, they weren't interested in Cambodia.

David and his wife, who became an Internet sensation after living under quarantine on a video site, were diagnosed with a new coronavirus on Feb. 18 and were waiting to be taken to a local Japanese hospital for treatment.

Wei Qingqing, who stepped off the diamond princess on Feb. 19, is far from finished fighting the new coronavirus. He will register a new account on social media to record his new 14 days in the FO Tan Quarantine Zone in Hong Kong, New Territories, China.

Where does the cruise ship go

##Where does the cruise ship go

The Chinese crew member of the Diamond Princess, Zhang Chi, is still at work, shuttling between stores and guest rooms during his four-hour days. The rest of the time he tried to stay in his room.

The tiny room only has room for a single bed, a TV cabinet and a TV. On a cruise ship where thousands of people share the Internet, video and voice calls are often a luxury. Because there were no windows, the room went dark when the lights were turned off.

For a long time, he felt suffocated in the room, where he kept refreshing his news every day. Of the more than 600 confirmed patients, 20 were his crewmates, and the numbers kept rising.

But over time, he got used to his life. In the early hours of Feb. 19, when Caijing reporters asked Zhang Chi again about the conditions inside the cabin, his tone was much calmer, he was no longer thinking of the daily figures, of his own flimsy protective gear and of the Japanese government's increasingly unpopular rescue efforts.

The quarantine period ended on February 19 and all crew members were tested. The ship gave the crew two options: Go home or remain on the ship in quarantine. Zhang Chi wasn't too happy. The Japanese were close to home, but he was Chinese, a long way from home, and his neighborhood was sealed off. He didn't know what to expect.

In the future, one day at a time.

Since the 15th and 16th century, the history of human exploration at sea is actually a history of fighting with infectious diseases.

1509, smallpox was taken to the Hispaniola, and the island's Indian tribes were wiped out by smallpox. Smallpox then began a wild expansion in the Americas, 20 years later, the Aztec, the Inca civilization in the Americas under its raging decline.

In the 19th century, Britain brought cholera out of trade to China, Japan and Indonesia, and then north to Russia; in the early 20th century, it started with the plague in China, as sailboats became widely used around the world, it became an epidemic in the major international trading ports of Sydney, Mumbai, San Francisco, and Rio de Janeiro; by the 21st Century, norovirus had become the most alarming disease on ships today.

Humans are not helpless against viruses at sea. After so many centuries of struggle, modern cruise ships already have a sophisticated disinfection system, and the world has a standard response to viruses and epidemics.

The crew of the diamond princess told Caijing that the ship has a three-level alert response, such as the norovirus must be at least a three-level response, which means more than 1,000 crew members will have to stop their work, apply disinfectant every half hour in your area of responsibility and wipe the surfaces of the facilities with a cloth covered with the disinfectant for at least 10 seconds.

"fever and diarrhea are a very, very serious condition on a cruise ship, " the crew said. If the crew members have any symptoms, they must report them immediately, and if they report them more than half an hour later, they will be warned. And, whether it's fever or diarrhea, the crew will be quarantined for more than 24 hours.

The US Centers for Disease Control and Prevention has also developed a ship health plan (VSP) for the global cruise industry, the program operates under the authority of the Public Health Services Act (United States Code 42, Section 264, quarantine and Inspection Regulations for the control of Infectious Diseases) . VSP has a website to track all reported cruise ship outbreaks.

It is important to note that VSP monitoring covers gastrointestinal infections, not all of them. The respiratory tract infection may have been underestimated for a number of reasons, including a lack of diagnostic capacity on board and the fact that neither staff nor passengers knew to report such illnesses to health officials.

The new coronavirus is a virus underestimated by crew and VSP program, which is a new challenge to the whole shipping and cruise industry.

Not only how ships fight the disease, the diamond princess case may also affect future cruises in the disaster of international maritime regulations.

Several scholars and cruise ship operators interviewed by Caijing said that since the crew came from all over the world and tourists came from all over the world, it has been a world-class problem to define who is responsible for the accident.

In dealing with the issue of cruise ships, the home country of Britain beyond reach, chose the silence, and then hot potato Japan, the performance is unsatisfactory.

In a long post on social media in the early hours of Feb. 20, Ministry of Health, Labour and Welfare official Gao Shanyihao acknowledged that he was the official who helped Iwada board the ship and responded to many of the questions raised by Iwada in the video.

He points to the fact that cruises are strictly compartmentalised, "although it may not be perfect" . The suggestion about Iwada was not accepted, Gao said, "In addition to the DMAT, there are the Ministry of Health, Labour and Welfare, the self-defence forces and, most importantly, the captain-led cruise ship. There is a lot of decision-making going on and [ Mr Iwada ] doesn't understand the complexities. "

"If we just give the right advice, there's a chance that the organization won't work, especially in crisis management, where trust is more important than anything else, " Alpine said.

"Japan's decision to allow the diamond princess into Port of Yokohama is commendable compared to other countries' decisions to deny access, " said a longtime scholar of Japanese politics.

Few people are aware of the situation facing Japan itself: First, it is not an obligation that Japan must fulfil; second, japan needs to consider the limited availability of medical supplies, the risk of widespread spread in the country, the impact on the national economy, and the fate of each political party and politician. These complex and contradictory factors make the whole of Japan into a conflict, but also the diamond princess put the ship into danger.

Those who had disembarked looked lucky, but perhaps because they had been tested negative for the virus and let down their guard, they did not defend themselves very well. Judging from the photos, most of them don't even wear masks properly. Reporters gathered on the shore, most of them without masks.

Some people choose to be cautious. A Spanish couple and 15 Australian passengers refused to return to dry land for fear they would be infected in transit or infect others; some refused to leave their confirmed relatives behind.

Some people don't have a choice. According to Twitter User@cocorobyn  , his father and two other asymptomatic positive people were placed in the same isolation room as a patient with a fever after they got off the boat.

The port was cold in the winter, and for weeks the diamond princess had stood unemotional on the water, as weary passengers stepped out onto the terrace, from where the flag had been raised, to ask for help, until now they have stared at the mottled surface of the ship, while visitors without balconies can only look up at the ceiling and Sigh. Today, many of them have been taken off the ship, even back to their own countries, some will be re-quarantined on the ship, but again, they are the virus "victims. ".

When 1492 Columbus made his first voyage to the Americas, the world's ecosystems changed dramatically, the old and new worlds became one, and humanity began to cope with viruses and pandemics together.

There is no doubt that the new coronavirus is not an epidemic in China, nor in Japan, nor in a city, nor on a cruise ship, but in the world, and no one can really stay out of it.
